comments.body: Not sure I can quite make out from the photo clues on age, though it does look like there is a warm chestnut color on the wing coverts. Peter' Pyle's Identification Guide to North American Birds does appear to confirm that many hatch year Black Phoebes still identifiable this time of year. (Can't say I had tracked the molt on these before.) For reference, here are notes on juvenile plumage from Birds of North American Online: Similar to Definitive Basic (adult) plumage except black areas darker than in adult; feathers of lower back, lower scapulars, rump, and uppertail-coverts indistinctly tipped with pale brownish; posterior margin of black on breast, more or less strongly washed with brownish or rusty fulvous; wing coverts, primaries, and secondaries tipped with cinnamon or light rusty; white of underparts suffused along border with brown or rusty. Tips of Juvenile rectrices also less rounded than those of adult (Pyle 1997c).
